<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06058329 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06058329 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; -- Ron Schlesser  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  FOOD; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  WHEN CUSTOMERS come to Decadence, Ron Schlesser's Fremont hair salon,Schlesser loves pampering them with his flair for style. At home, he takespleasure in creating decadently delicious meals for his friends and family.;   Ron credits his parents with encouraging him to develop his artistic skills.&quot;When I was growing up, I would rather be in the kitchen cooking up somethingwonderful with my mother and my aunt than mowing the lawns. Both Canadians, myMom and Aunt Dorothy taught me the good, old basics like pizza, lasagna,goulash, shepherd's pie, omelets and different ways to cook poached eggs.&quot;  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  The Weekly, Part 2  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  HAIR STYLIST PAMPERS CLIENTS, FAMILYSCHLESSER'S CULINARY INTEREST SHOWED UP EARLY  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  The Weekly Cook  </MEMO><TEXT>     When Ron went to high school, he took culinary arts at a time when boysdidn't consider it particularly macho. &quot;I took it with two other guys, and thegirls thought we were all weird,&quot; he said. &quot;The funny thing was, we came outat the top of our class that year and left the girls behind.&quot;;    Ron hasalways enjoyed using his gift of creativity to help people feel good aboutthemselves. His first successes at styling hair for neighborhood friends atage 16 led him to a different type of creative occupation.;    &quot;I became alicensed psychology technician and worked with the mentally handicapped forseveral years,&quot; he said. &quot;It was difficult and depressing because I put myheart and soul into it and they didn't get any better.&quot;;    Ten years ago, herealized that he could combine his psychology skills with design skills. &quot;Acosmetologist must be a psychologist because they have to fit the proper styleto match people's personalities and tastes,&quot; he said. &quot;I decided to sign upfor beauty school in Modesto, at California Beauty College and have neverlooked back.&quot;;    Opening his own salon challenged his talents. &quot;I wanted tohave a unique place that would make people feel comfortable as soon as theyset foot in the door,&quot; he said. He opened Decadence last September. Among thefeatures, he serves customers gourmet coffee and chocolates.;    When he comeshome from a long day at the salon, he relaxes in the kitchen, cooking for hiswife, Denise, and 9-month old baby, Alivia.;    &quot;I am basically a homebody. Myfamily means everything to me,&quot; he said. &quot;I like to develop my own Chinese orItalian style recipes for them and especially like cooking one pot meals.&quot;;    DECADENT CHEESE POTATOES;  8 medium potatoes, washed, skin left on and slicedthinly;  4 cups sharp cheddar cheese, grated;  4 cups Monterrey Jack cheese,grated;  12 tablespoons sour cream;  1 cup chopped green onion;  2 clovesgarlic, chopped;  1 teaspoon half and half;  Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Onthe bottom of an 8-by-10-inch glass pan, spread 4 tablespoons of the sourcream. Top with a layer of potatoes and sprinkle with one-third of thecheeses, the green onion and the garlic. Repeat until the pan is full. Topwith sour cream and sprinkle with the teaspoon of half and half. Bake inpreheated oven for 1 1/2 hours, or, microwave at full power for 50 minutesrotating the dish halfway through the cooking time.;     MEAL IN ONE;  6skinned chicken breasts; 4 medium potatoes, peeled and chopped;  1 cup ofwine;  1/2 cup of vinegar;  1/2 cup chopped green onion;  2 cloves garlic,chopped;  2 cups of your favorite green vegetable;  1 large can stewedtomatoes, drained;  2 cups of cheese;   salt and pepper to taste;   On thebottom of a large casserole, evenly layer the potatoes, chicken, green onion,garlic, vegetables, and tomatoes. Pour the wine and vinegar over the layeredingredients. Sprinkle the cheese over the top. In a 375-degree oven, bakecovered for 30 minutes. Take off the cover and bake an additional 15 minutes.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Holly Rudin-Braschi column  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Alameda County/AM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910227  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  February  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  632  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday February 27, 199100058329,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>